nda|last=Hildebrand-----|first=Nick|work=The Herald|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nKelly was born on May 10, 1948, in Pittsburgh, PA. He has spent most of his life in [[Butler, Pennsylvania|Butler]], a city north of Pittsburgh. He played varsity football as a [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]] in high school, and his team reached two [[WPIAL]] championship games. He graduated from [[Butler High School (Butler, Pennsylvania)|Butler High School]] in 1966. He received a scholarship to play football at [[University of Notre Dame]], but his playing ended because of an injury.\n\nAfter college, he worked for his father's [[Chevrolet]]/[[Cadillac]] car dealership. In 1995, he purchased his father's business, and then added [[Hyundai]] and [[Kia Motors|KIA]] to his dealership lineup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpxi.com/politics/25102516/detail.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107040659/http://www.wpxi.com/politics/25102516/detail.html |archivedate=2011-01-07 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKelly is a former member of the Butler City Council.\n\n==United States House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010#District 3}}\nKelly challenged incumbent Rep. [[Kathy Dahlkemper]] in 2010.<ref>http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbs.dll/article?AID=/20101103/NEWS02/311029900/-1/news</ref> He won the election by 10%,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://projects.usatoday.com/news/politics/2010/elections/?loc=interstitialskip|title=USA TODAY: Latest World and US News  - USATODAY.com|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> largely by running up his margins outside of heavily Democratic Erie.\n\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012#District 3}}\nKelly defeated Democrat Missa Eaton 55%\u201341%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/PA|title=2016 Election Results: President Live Map by State, Real-Time Voting Updates|website=Election Hub|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> His district had been made slightly friendlier in redistricting. The district was pushed slightly to the south, absorbing some rural and Republican territory east of Pittsburgh.\n\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2014#District 3}}\nKelly defeated Democrat Dan LaVallee of Cranberry Township 60.5%-39.5%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2014/pennsylvania-elections|title=Pennsylvania Election Results|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>\n; 2016\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2016#District 3|l1=United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2016 \u00a7 District 3}}\n\nKelly ran unopposed and received 100% of the vote.\n\n;2018\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2018#District 3}}\nKelly represented the 3rd Congressional District, but due to redistricting, he is running for the 16th Congressional District in Pennsylvania in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/02/19/upshot/pennsylvania-new-house-districts-gerrymandering.html?rref=collection/sectioncollection/upshot&action=click&contentCollection=upshot&region=rank&module=package&version=highlights&contentPlacement=1&pgtype=sectionfront|title=The New Pennsylvania Congressional Map, District by District|last=Cohn|first=Nate|date=|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPoliticsPA wrote that Kelly's seat might not be one of the seats considered safe for re-election. Public Policy Polling found that Kelly had a 48% to 43% lead over Democratic opponent [[Ron DiNicola]]. According to the same poll, Kelly has a job approval rating of just 38%, with a 41% disapproval rating.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politicspa.com/ppp-poll-mike-kelly-under-50-percent-threshold-for-re-election/87716/|title=PoliticsPA|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Ratings ===\nKelly has received the following ratings from advocacy organizations:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/mike_kelly/412465|title=Mike Kelly, Representative for Pennsylvania's 3rd Congressional District - GovTrack.us|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\n* [[United States Chamber of Commerce]]: 95%\n* [[Club for Growth|The Club for Growth]]: 71%\n* [[FreedomWorks]]: 55%\n* The National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws: D\n* [[American Civil Liberties Union]]: 5%\n* [[League of Conservation Voters]]: 4%\n* [[Planned Parenthood]] Action Fund: 4%\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means]]\n\nIn addition, Kelly serves as the co-chair of the Northeast-Midwest Congressional Coalition, a bipartisan group of U.S. Representatives from the 18 Northeastern and Midwestern States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nemw.org/index.php/congressional-coalitions-and-task-forces/northeast-midwest-congressional-coalition|title=Northeast-Midwest Insititute   \u00bb The Northeast-Midwest Congressional Coalition|website=www.nemw.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Automotive Caucus\n* Congressional Coal Caucus\n* Job Creators Caucus\n* Natural Gas Caucus\n* Sportsman's Caucus\n* Congressional Caucus on Korea\n* Congressional Services Caucus\n* Congressional Manufacturing Caucus\n* Congressional Steel Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n* Marcellus Shale Caucus\n* [[Congressional Prayer Caucus]]\n* Pro-Life Caucus\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== \"Deep state\" remarks ===\nWhen speaking at a Mercer County Republican Party event in 2017, Kelly advanced the [[conspiracy theory]] that former president Barack Obama was running a \"[[Shadow government (conspiracy)|shadow government]]\" to undermine President Trump.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/03/11/gop-congressman-offers-strange-obama-conspiracy-theory-and-even-stranger-explanations/|title=Analysis {{!}} GOP congressman offers strange Obama conspiracy theory \u2014 and even stranger explanations|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/early-returns/erstate/2017/03/10/Philly-Clout-Mike-Kelly-s-Obama-conspiracy-theory-was-supposed-to-be-private/stories/201703100184|title=Kelly backtracks on claim of Obama|work=Early Returns:|access-date=2017-03-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/pennsylvania/statements/2017/mar/14/mike-kelly/western-pa-congressman-backs-strange-obama-shadow-/|title=Western PA congressman backs off \u2018strange\u2019 Obama shadow gove|work=@politifact|access-date=2017-03-15|language=en}}</ref>  When asked about these remarks, Kelly said that they were meant to be private.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/clout/clout-conspiracy-theory-congressman.html|title=Philly Clout: Congressman's conspiracy theory was supposed to be 'private'|work=Philly.com|access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> After the remarks made national news, Kelly's spokesperson said that Kelly did not believe that Obama \"is personally operating a shadow government\".<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Environment ===\nSpeaking at a [[Heritage Foundation]] event in July 2014, Kelly compared the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] to [[terrorists]] while attacking EPA regulations  limiting power plant emissions, saying \"You talk about terrorism \u2013 you can do it in a lot of different ways,... But you terrorize the people who supply everything this country needs to be great \u2013 and you keep them on the sidelines \u2013 my goodness, what have we become?\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thinkprogress.org/climate/2014/07/28/3465030/house-republican-climate-rule-terrorism/|title=Congressman Compares EPA\u2019s New Climate Rule To Terrorism|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Kelly was rated 0% by the Clean Water Action group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/119463/mike-kelly-jr#.W6vqkBMzZ5M|title=Mike Kelly, Jr.'s Political Summary|last=|first=|date=|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nOn August 1, 2012, Kelly called the [[Contraceptive mandate (United States)|HHS mandate]] of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) - which requires health insurers or employers that provide their employees with health insurance to cover some [[Contraception|contraceptive]] costs in their health insurance plans - an attack on Americans' constitutionally protected religious rights and that August 1, 2012, would go down in infamy as \"the day that religious freedom died\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cnsnews.com/news/article/congressman-were-still-home-brave-were-not-land-free-anymore|title=Congressman: 'We're Still Home of the Brave, But We're Not the Land of the Free Anymore'|website=CNS News|language=en|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Redistricting==\nWhen Kelly was elected, the district was located in the northwestern corner of the state, stretching from [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]] to rural territory near [[Pittsburgh]]. In February 2018, after the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] ruled the Pennsylvania districts to be unconstitutionally [[Gerrymandering|gerrymandered]], most of his district will become the [[Pennsylvania's 16th congressional district|16th District]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nKelly lives in [[Butler, Pennsylvania|Butler]], Pennsylvania, with his wife, Victoria. They have four children, George&nbsp;III, Brendan, Charlotte, and Colin, and ten grandchildren.<ref>http://www.mikekellyforcongress.com/mikes-story/</ref> He is the brother-in-law of [[Tennessee's 1st congressional district]] Congressman [[Phil Roe (politician)|Phil Roe]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://kelly.house.gov/ Congressman Mike Kelly] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.mikekellyforcongress.com/ Mike Kelly for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mike_Kelly_%5BR-3%5D|Mike Kelly}}\n* {{C-SPAN|mikekelly03}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=K000376 | votesmart=119463 | fec=H0PA03271 | congress=mike-kelly/2051 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kathy Dahlkemper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Pennsylvania|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Pennsylvania's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William R. Keating|William Keating]]<br>D-[[Massachusetts]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority